Sure, here's an example of a basic Chrome extension that runs a specific JavaScript code after a page is loaded on a specific URL:

1. Create a new folder for your extension and give it a name.
2. Create a manifest.json file in the root of your extension folder. Here's an example of what the manifest.json file should look like:
```
{
  "manifest_version": 2,
  "name": "My Extension",
  "version": "1.0",
  "description": "Description of my extension",
  "permissions": [
    "activeTab"
  ],
  "content_scripts": [
    {
      "matches": [
        "https://www.example.com/*"
      ],
      "js": [
        "contentScript.js"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```
3. Create a contentScript.js file in the root of your extension folder. This file will contain the JavaScript code that will be injected into the page after it is loaded on the specified URL. Here's an example of what the contentScript.js file should look like:
```
console.log("Content script loaded");
```
4. To load your extension into Chrome and test it, use the Chrome Extension Developer Tool to load your extension.
5. Once you are satisfied with your extension, you can package it into a .zip file and submit it to the Chrome Web Store for others to download and use.

Note: The "activeTab" permission is required to run content scripts in response to a URL.

Also, you can use `chrome.tabs.executeScript()` to inject scripts into a specific tab.
```
chrome.tabs.executeScript({
    code: 'console.log("Content script loaded")'
});
```
This method is useful when you want to run script on a page that is not yet loaded, or when you want to run script on multiple pages.
